    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. Could you go a bit deeper into how they actually intercept the traffic? Like, what are the common methods they use to sit in the middle of the data flow? I've heard something about ARP spoofing but I don't really get how that helps them.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, ARP spoofing, or ARP poisoning, is a commonly used method for MitM attacks in this context. When you connect to a Wi-Fi network, your device needs to know the IP address of the gateway (the router) it should send data to. With ARP, devices use the Address Resolution Protocol to map an IP address to a physical hardware address (MAC address). Now picture an attacker using ARP spoofing: they respond faster than any legitimate reply in your local network area. So when your computer contacts the router and requests this IP-to-MAC address translation, the attacker immediately replies with the translation of the genuine network router's IP to a different, malleable device’s MAC address that they control. Therefore, all the data intended for the router is routed to the attacker, who can then capture or alter this information without either the originating device or the genuine router knowing. This allows them to potentially eavesdrop, inject malicious traffic, or even impersonate the router to hijack network sessions. It’s a technique based on exploiting the inherently trustful and stateless nature of the ARP protocol. Preventing such attacks often involves adopting the use of secure, encrypted protocols like IPSec or IKEv2",
      "source": "target",
